## Source Coverage

Briefly describe what parts of the Core North-Star were retained.

Use bullets.

Then briefly describe what parts were intentionally excluded.

Use bullets.

## Protected Epic Identity

Define the semantic identity that must be preserved during realignment.

| ID | Protected Identity Element | Source Reference | Realignment Consequence |
|---|---|---|---|

Examples of Protected Identity Element:

- strategic purpose
- desired capability
- core problem
- projection link
- canonical domain concept
- invariant boundary
- intended user or system outcome

Realignment Consequence should explain what the downstream prompt must preserve.

## Mutable Epic Regions

Define which regions of an epic may be changed during realignment.

| ID | Mutable Region | Allowed Changes | Required Guardrail |
|---|---|---|---|

Examples of Mutable Region:

- title
- strategic purpose wording
- desired capability wording
- projection link
- scope
- non-goals
- assumptions
- dependencies
- constraints
- acceptance criteria
- success conditions
- risks / watchpoints
- required follow-up
- traceability

Required Guardrail should explain how the region may change without altering epic identity.

## Transformation Rules

Define how the realignment patch should be applied.

| ID | Transformation Rule | Meaning | Required Behavior |
|---|---|---|---|

Include rules for:

- minimal semantic patching
- audit-supported changes only
- identity preservation
- projection vocabulary preservation
- no speculative expansion
- no repository re-audit
- no implementation planning
- preserve unaffected sections
- remove stale or contradicted content
- merge duplicates

## Patch Constraints

Define what the downstream prompt must not do while realigning.

| ID | Constraint | Reason | Violation Indicates |
|---|---|---|---|

Violation Indicates should say whether the violation suggests:

- Reimagine required
- Retire required
- Insufficient Evidence
- Different prompt required
- Governance / roadmap process required

Examples of constraints:

- do not change strategic purpose
- do not create a new initiative
- do not split the epic
- do not generate milestones
- do not produce implementation tasks
- do not modify roadmap
- do not copy raw audit detail
- do not add unsupported scope

## Alignment Rules

Define how the realigned epic should remain aligned with the Core.

| ID | Alignment Rule | Applies To | Realignment Implication |
|---|---|---|---|

Applies To may include:

- strategic purpose
- desired capability
- scope
- dependencies
- constraints
- acceptance criteria
- success conditions
- terminology
- risks

## Consistency Rules

Define internal consistency requirements after realignment.

| ID | Consistency Rule | Trigger | Required Update |
|---|---|---|---|

Examples:

- If scope is narrowed, acceptance criteria must be narrowed.
- If dependency is added, assumptions and risks must reflect it.
- If constraint is added, success conditions must preserve it.
- If terminology is normalized, all affected sections must use the canonical term.
- If stale content is removed, related references must be removed or corrected.
- If a non-goal is added, scope must not contradict it.

## Escalation Boundaries

Define when a requested change exceeds Realign.

| ID | Boundary | Indicates | Required Handling |
|---|---|---|---|

Indicates must be one of:

- Reimagine
- Retire
- Insufficient Evidence
- Roadmap Revision
- Different Prompt Required

Examples:

- protected identity would change
- desired capability would become a different capability
- epic would need to split or merge
- strategic purpose is no longer valid
- audit evidence is insufficient for a safe patch
- roadmap sequencing must change before the epic can be updated
- implementation planning is being requested

## Traceability Requirements

Define how changes must trace to audit findings and Core semantics.

| ID | Traceability Requirement | Required Evidence | Failure Handling |
|---|---|---|---|

Examples:

- every material change must cite an audit finding
- every preserved identity element must trace to the Core or projection
- every new constraint must trace to projection or audit
- every dependency change must trace to audit
- every removed claim must be contradicted or superseded by audit evidence

Failure Handling should explain whether to omit the change, flag uncertainty, or block realignment.

## Canonical Vocabulary

List load-bearing terms that downstream prompts must preserve.

| Term | Definition | Notes / Banned Synonyms |
|---|---|---|

Rules:

- Include only terms relevant to epic realignment.
- Use Core definitions where available.
- If a term is undefined in the Core but required for this projection, mark definition as “Projection-local; confirm against Core if promoted.”

